:"1145","1265":"1265","circa 1245":"omkring 1245","Holland":"Nederlandene"},"nl":{"circa 1165–circa 1245":"circa 1165–circa 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1170–1250":"1170–1250","1190–1265":"1190–1265","1195–1251":"1195–1251","1130–Male":"1130–Overleden","1145–Female":"1145–Overleden","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","circa 1190":"circa 1190","1130":"1130","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","circa 1165":"circa 1165","1245":"1245","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","circa 1245":"circa 1245","Holland":"Nederland"},"en":{"circa 1165–circa 1245":"about 1165–about 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1170–1250":"1170–1250","1190–1265":"1190–1265","1195–1251":"1195–1251","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","circa 1190":"about 1190","1130":"1130","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","circa 1165":"about 1165","1245":"1245","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","circa 1245":"about 1245","Holland":"Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Richbold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Richold</i>,  <i>Rikold</i>, used of both men and women. The male name is an Old French form of Continental Germanic  <i>Ricoald</i>,  <i>Ricold</i>,  <i>Richold</i> and the female name is an Old French form of Continental Germanic  <i>Richold</i>, a variant of  <i>Richild</i>;  compare  Rickell   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rickel","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place in Haspengau (near Lüttich) named Rickel.","German: from a female ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Riclind</i>.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>walt-</i> ‘rule’."]},{"name":"Rickwood","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Richeward</i>,  <i>Rikeward</i> (Old French  <i>Ricoart</i>, Continental Germanic  <i>Ricward</i>). Some examples may belong under (2).","2  Norman, English: occasionally perhaps a variant of   Richold  ."]},{"name":"Rickell","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Riccall (ER Yorks), near Selby.","2  Norman, English: relationship name, occasionally perhaps from the Middle English female personal name  <i>Richild</i>,  <i>Rikild</i> (Continental Germanic  <i>Richild</i>,  <i>Richeld</i>).  See  Richold  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richbold II van Ochten  was born about 1165, in Netherlands, his father, Hendrik van VOORST, was 37 and his mother, N. Richboldsdr van Ochten., was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Maria van Bentheim. He died about 1245, at the age of 82."},"et":{"circa 1165–circa 1245":"umbes 1165–umbes 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1170–1250":"1170–1250","1190–1265":"1190–1265","1195–1251":"1195–1251","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","circa 1190":"umbes 1190","1130":"1130","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","circa 1165":"umbes 1165","1245":"1245","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","circa 1245":"umbes 1245","Holland":"Madalmaad"},"fi":{"circa 1165–circa 1245":"noin 1165–noin 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1170–1250":"1170–1250","1190–1265":"1190–1265","1195–1251":"1195–1251","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","circa 1190":"noin 1190","1130":"1130","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","circa 1165":"noin 1165","1245":"1245","1145":"1145","1265":"1265","circa 1245":"noin 1245","Holland":"Alankomaat"},"fr":{"circa 1165–circa 1245":"environ 1165–environ 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1170–1250":"1170–1250","1190–1265":"1190–1265","1195–1251":"1195–1251","1130–Male":"1